Occupancy Detection Classification Project¶

Goal¶

The goal of this project is to implement and compare three different classification algorithms—Random Forest, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)—to predict room occupancy based on environmental sensor data such as temperature, humidity, light, CO2, and humidity ratio. We will evaluate the performance of these models using 10-fold cross-validation and calculate various performance metrics manually.

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Dataset Description¶

Dataset Name: Occupancy Detection Data Set
Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository
URL: Occupancy Detection Data Set
Description: The dataset contains experimental data used for binary classification (room occupancy) from temperature, humidity, light, and CO2 measurements. Ground-truth occupancy was obtained from time-stamped pictures taken every minute.

1.2 Features¶

  • date: Date and time (year-month-day hour:minute:second)
  • Temperature: Temperature in degrees Celsius
  • Humidity: Relative humidity in %
  • Light: Light intensity in Lux
  • CO2: CO2 concentration in parts per million (ppm)
  • HumidityRatio: Derived quantity from temperature and relative humidity
  • Occupancy: Target variable (0 for unoccupied, 1 for occupied)

1.3 Objective¶

Predict: Whether a room is occupied or not based on sensor data.
Algorithms Used:

  • Random Forest
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM)
  • Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)

Evaluation Metrics:

  • True Positive (TP)
  • True Negative (TN)
  • False Positive (FP)
  • False Negative (FN)
  • True Positive Rate (TPR)
  • True Negative Rate (TNR)
  • False Positive Rate (FPR)
  • False Negative Rate (FNR)
  • Precision
  • F1 Score
  • Accuracy
  • Error Rate
  • Balanced Accuracy (BACC)
  • True Skill Statistic (TSS)
  • Heidke Skill Score (HSS)
  • Area Under ROC Curve (AUC)
  • Brier Score

7. Defining Metrics Calculation Function¶

We will define a function to manually calculate performance metrics such as TPR, TNR, Precision, F1 Score, Accuracy, and others.

In [16]:
def calculate_metrics(y_true, y_pred):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    if cm.shape == (2, 2):
        TN, FP, FN, TP = cm.ravel()
    else:
        TN = FP = FN = TP = 0
    # Calculations
    P = TP + FN
    N = TN + FP
    TPR = TP / P if P != 0 else 0
    TNR = TN / N if N != 0 else 0
    FPR = FP / N if N != 0 else 0
    FNR = FN / P if P != 0 else 0
    Precision = TP / (TP + FP) if (TP + FP) != 0 else 0
    F1_measure = 2 * TP / (2 * TP + FP + FN) if (2 * TP + FP + FN) != 0 else 0
    Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (P + N) if (P + N) != 0 else 0
    Error_rate = (FP + FN) / (P + N) if (P + N) != 0 else 0
    BACC = (TPR + TNR) / 2
    TSS = TPR - FPR
    HSS = (2 * (TP * TN - FP * FN)) / ((P * (FN + TN)) + ((TP + FP) * (FP + TN))) if ((P * (FN + TN)) + ((TP + FP) * (FP + TN))) != 0 else 0
    return {
        'TP': TP, 'TN': TN, 'FP': FP, 'FN': FN,
        'TPR': TPR, 'TNR': TNR, 'FPR': FPR, 'FNR': FNR,
        'Precision': Precision, 'F1_measure': F1_measure,
        'Accuracy': Accuracy, 'Error_rate': Error_rate,
        'BACC': BACC, 'TSS': TSS, 'HSS': HSS
    }

8. Modeling and Evaluation¶

8.1 Lists to Store Metrics¶

In [17]:
rf_metrics_list = []
svm_metrics_list = []
lstm_metrics_list = []

8.2 Cross-Validation Loop¶

In [ ]:
fold = 1
for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X):
    print(f"Fold {fold}:")

    # Split the data
    X_train, X_test = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[test_index]

    ### Random Forest ###
    rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
    rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    rf_pred = rf_model.predict(X_test)
    rf_pred_prob = rf_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Predicted probabilities
    rf_metrics = calculate_metrics(y_test, rf_pred)
    rf_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, rf_pred_prob)
    rf_brier = brier_score_loss(y_test, rf_pred_prob)  # Calculate Brier Score
    rf_metrics['AUC'] = rf_auc
    rf_metrics['Brier_score'] = rf_brier  #  Brier Score to metrics
    rf_metrics_list.append(rf_metrics)


    ### Support Vector Machine ###
    svm_model = SVC(kernel='linear', probability=True, random_state=42)
    svm_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    svm_pred = svm_model.predict(X_test)
    svm_pred_prob = svm_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Predicted probabilities
    svm_metrics = calculate_metrics(y_test, svm_pred)
    svm_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, svm_pred_prob)
    svm_brier = brier_score_loss(y_test, svm_pred_prob)  # Calculate Brier Score
    svm_metrics['AUC'] = svm_auc
    svm_metrics['Brier_score'] = svm_brier  #  Brier Score to metrics
    svm_metrics_list.append(svm_metrics)


    ### LSTM ###
    # Reshape data for LSTM
    X_train_lstm = np.array(X_train).reshape((X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], 1))
    X_test_lstm = np.array(X_test).reshape((X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1], 1))
    y_train_lstm = np.array(y_train)
    y_test_lstm = np.array(y_test)

    lstm_model = Sequential()
    lstm_model.add(LSTM(64, input_shape=(X_train_lstm.shape[1], 1)))
    lstm_model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    lstm_model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    lstm_model.fit(X_train_lstm, y_train_lstm, epochs=5, batch_size=32, verbose=0)
    lstm_pred_prob = lstm_model.predict(X_test_lstm)
    lstm_pred = (lstm_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int).reshape(-1)
    lstm_metrics = calculate_metrics(y_test_lstm, lstm_pred)
    lstm_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test_lstm, lstm_pred_prob)
    lstm_brier = brier_score_loss(y_test_lstm, lstm_pred_prob)  # Calculate Brier Score
    lstm_metrics['AUC'] = lstm_auc
    lstm_metrics['Brier_score'] = lstm_brier  #  Brier Score to metrics
    lstm_metrics_list.append(lstm_metrics)


    # Print metrics for the fold
    print(f"Random Forest Accuracy: {rf_metrics['Accuracy']:.2f}, AUC: {rf_metrics['AUC']:.2f}")
    print(f"SVM Accuracy: {svm_metrics['Accuracy']:.2f}, AUC: {svm_metrics['AUC']:.2f}")
    print(f"LSTM Accuracy: {lstm_metrics['Accuracy']:.2f}, AUC: {lstm_metrics['AUC']:.2f}")
    print("------------------------------------------------------")
    fold +=1

10. Discussion¶

Performance Summary¶

Random Forest:¶

  • Average Accuracy: 0.9932
  • Average AUC: 0.9989
  • Other Metrics:
    • True Positive Rate (TPR): 0.9891
    • True Negative Rate (TNR): 0.9945
    • Precision: 0.9818
    • F1 Score: 0.9854
    • Error Rate: 0.0068
    • Brier Score: 0.0052

Support Vector Machine (SVM):¶

  • Average Accuracy: 0.9890
  • Average AUC: 0.9944
  • Other Metrics:
    • True Positive Rate (TPR): 0.9960
    • True Negative Rate (TNR): 0.9868
    • Precision: 0.9579
    • F1 Score: 0.9765
    • Error Rate: 0.0110
    • Brier Score: 0.0107

Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM):¶

  • Average Accuracy: 0.9887
  • Average AUC: 0.9967
  • Other Metrics:
    • True Positive Rate (TPR): 0.9947
    • True Negative Rate (TNR): 0.9868
    • Precision: 0.9578
    • F1 Score: 0.9759
    • Error Rate: 0.0113
    • Brier Score: 0.0102

Observations¶

Exceptional Model Performance:¶

  • All models achieved high classification performance, with accuracies ranging from 98.87% to 99.32% and AUCs close to 1.00.
  • High TPR and TNR indicate effective identification of both occupied and unoccupied instances.

Random Forest Outperformed Other Models:¶

  • Random Forest achieved the highest accuracy (99.32%) and AUC (99.89%), outperforming SVM and LSTM.
  • It had the lowest error rate and Brier Score, which indicates better calibration and reliability.
  • SVM and LSTM had slightly lower accuracies and higher error rates, with SVM showing marginally higher TPR but lower TNR compared to Random Forest.

Effectiveness of Features:¶

  • Features such as Light and CO2 are highly predictive of occupancy.
  • The environmental sensor data provided sufficient information for accurate predictions.

Possible Reasons for High Performance¶

  1. High Predictive Power of Features:

    • Environmental sensor data captures conditions directly influenced by human presence.
    • For instance, CO2 levels and light intensity increase when a room is occupied.

  2. Data Quality and Consistency:

    • Clean dataset with no missing values, collected under controlled conditions.
    • Consistent data collection methods enhanced the models' reliability.

  3. Model Capabilities:

    • Random Forest: Handles nonlinear relationships effectively and is robust to overfitting.
    • SVM: Finds the optimal separating hyperplane but is sensitive to overlapping classes.
    • LSTM: Designed for sequential data; despite limited temporal information, it captured patterns effectively.

Considerations¶

  1. Class Imbalance:

    • Dataset is imbalanced with 76.90% unoccupied and 23.10% occupied instances.
    • SVM and LSTM showed slightly lower Precision and higher False Positives, reflecting potential impact of imbalance.
    • Future work could explore techniques like resampling, SMOTE, or adjusting class weights.

  2. Overfitting Potential:

    • Near-perfect performance suggests potential overfitting.
    • Additional validation on an independent test set is recommended to confirm generalizability.

  3. Model Complexity vs. Performance:

    • Random Forest is less computationally intensive than LSTM and achieved the highest accuracy.
    • SVM is computationally efficient but slightly underperformed compared to Random Forest.
    • For practical applications, model simplicity and resource efficiency are crucial.

Implications¶

  • The high accuracy across all models confirms that environmental sensor data is a strong indicator of room occupancy.
  • Random Forest is preferred for deployment due to its performance and computational efficiency.
  • These findings demonstrate the potential of machine learning models for energy management, security systems, and smart building applications, enhancing efficiency and automation.

11. Conclusion¶

In this project, we successfully implemented and compared three classification algorithms—Random Forest, SVM, and LSTM—on the Occupancy Detection dataset.

Key Findings¶

  • Random Forest outperformed both SVM and LSTM in terms of accuracy, AUC, and calibration (lower Brier Score).
    • Achieved an average accuracy of 99.32% and an AUC of 99.89%, which indicates excellent model performance.
  • All models demonstrated that environmental sensor data is highly effective for predicting room occupancy.

Recommendations¶

Model Selection:¶

  • Random Forest is recommended due to its superior performance, simplicity, faster training times, and ease of implementation.
  • It provides a balance between accuracy and computational efficiency, which makes it suitable for real-time systems.

Future Work Could:¶

  1. Explore Temporal Patterns:
    • Incorporate temporal features or sequences to enhance model performance, especially for LSTM, which is designed for sequential data.
  2. Address Class Imbalance:
    • Investigate resampling techniques (e.g., SMOTE) or adjust class weights during model training to improve robustness, particularly for models affected by higher false positives.
  3. Hyperparameter Tuning:
    • Perform extensive hyperparameter optimization using techniques like Grid Search or Random Search with cross-validation to achieve better performance and reduce overfitting.

Deployment Considerations:¶

  • Assess computational resources and latency requirements in practical applications.
  • Consider the scalability and maintenance of the model within the system architecture.
  • Ensure model interpretability and transparency, particularly in contexts where explainability is crucial.

Final Thoughts¶

The findings demonstrate the feasibility and effectiveness of implementing predictive models for room occupancy detection using environmental sensor data. Random Forest, in particular, provides an efficient and highly accurate solution that can be integrated into smart building systems to optimize energy usage and enhance security.

Benefits of Model Integration:¶

  1. Energy Efficiency:
    • Automated control of heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems based on occupancy.
  2. Security Enhancements:
    • Improved monitoring and detection of unauthorized occupancy.
  3. Cost Savings:
    • Reduced energy consumption leads to financial savings and environmental benefits.
